.TH KIRC 1 "December 2025"
.SH NAME
kirc \- a tiny, dependency-light IRC client
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B kirc
.RB [<options>]
.RB <nickname>
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B kirc
is an extremely fast and simple IRC client designed with portability in mind,
following the "Keep It Simple, Stupid" (KISS) philosophy. It provides a
keyboard-driven interface for IRC communication.
.PP
This client reads from STDIN and prints to STDOUT, so all traffic can be
multiplexed and text parsed or modified using external commands. All highlighted
text and color can be controlled with ANSI escape sequences.
.PP
For best results and rendering, use a terminal emulator with 256 color support,
such as xterm-256color.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-s " server"
Specifies IRC server hostname. 
Default: irc.libera.chat
.TP
.BI \-p " port"
Specifies IRC server port.
Default: 6667
.TP
.BI \-c " channel(s)"
Specifies the channel(s) to JOIN (comma or pipe separated). Note that the first
channel in the list will be used as the default messaging channel after startup.
.TP
.BI \-r " realname"
Specifies the user's real name. By default, the client uses the nickname during
the initial connection
.TP
.BI \-u " username"
Specifies the USER connection username. By default, the client will assume the
username to be the nickname during the initial connection
.TP
.BI \-k " password"
Specifies the plain text PASS connection value associated with the respective
username or nickname
.TP
.BI \-a " auth"
Specifies SASL authentication mechanism and token value to be used. The argument
value is comprised of a colon-delimited string, where the first token is equal
to the mechanism (i.e. "PLAIN", "EXTERNAL", etc.) and the second string is the
BASE64 encoded authentication token (e.g. "PLAIN:amlsbGVzAGppbGxlcwBzZXNhbWU=")
.SH ENVIRONMENT
The following environment variables can be used to set defaults, which will be
overridden by command-line options:
.TP
.B KIRC_SERVER
Default IRC server hostname
.TP
.B KIRC_PORT
Default server port
.TP
.B KIRC_CHANNELS
Default channels to join (comma or pipe separated)
.TP
.B KIRC_REALNAME
Default real name
.TP
.B KIRC_USERNAME
Default username
.TP
.B KIRC_PASSWORD
Default password
.TP
.B KIRC_AUTH
Default SASL authentication token
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.BI /<command>
Send a raw IRC command to the server (e.g. /JOIN, /PART, /WHOIS, etc.)
.TP
.BI /set " <target>"
Set the default message channel or nickname to 
.I <target>
.TP
.BI <message>
Send PRIVMSG to set target nickname or channel with 
.I <message>
as the content
.TP
.BI @<target> " <message>"
Send
.I <message>
to a specified
.I <target>
nickname or channel
.TP
.BI /me " <action>"
Send CTCP
.I <action>
to set target nickname or channel
.TP
.BI /ctcp " <target> <command>"
send a raw CTCP
.I <command>
(e.g. "CLIENTINFO", "DCC", "PING", "TIME", and "VERSION") to
.I <target>
nickname or channel
.SH KEY BINDINGS
.TP
.B CTRL+C
Force quit kirc
.TP
.B CTRL+U
Delete entire line
.TP
.B Arrow Left (or CTRL+B)
Move cursor left
.TP
.B Arrow Right (or CTRL+F)
Move cursor right
.TP
.B Arrow Up (or CTRL+P)
Navigate command history (previous)
.TP
.B Arrow Down (or CTRL+N)
Navigate command history (next)
.TP
.B Home (or CTRL+A)
Move cursor to start of line
.TP
.B End (or CTRL+E)
Move cursor to end of line
.TP
.B Delete
Delete character at cursor
.TP
.B Backspace (or CTRL+H)
Delete character before cursor
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B kirc alice
Connect with nickname 'alice' to the default server (irc.libera.chat:6667) and join #chat
.TP
.B kirc \-s irc.example.org \-p 6667 \-c "#foo,#bar" alice
Connect to irc.example.org on port 6667 and join channels #foo and #bar
.TP
.B KIRC_SERVER=irc.libera.chat KIRC_PORT=6697 kirc alice
Use environment variables to set server and port
.TP
.B kirc alice | tee -a kirc-$(date +%Y%m%d).log
Connect and create a log file with current date as the title
.TP
.B kirc \-a \\[dq]PLAIN:$(printf \[aq]%s\0%s\0%s\[aq] \[aq]alice\[aq] \[aq]alice\[aq] \[aq]password\[aq] | base64)\\[dq] alice
Generate a BASE64 authentication token and connect using the SASL PLAIN mechanism
.TP
.B socat tcp-listen:6667,reuseaddr,fork,bind=127.0.0.1 ssl:irc.example.org:6697 & kirc -s 127.0.0.1 alice
Connect to irc.example.org with TLS/SSL support using socat.
.TP
.B socat tcp-listen:6667,fork,reuseaddr,bind=127.0.0.1 proxy:<proxyurl>:irc.example.org:6667,proxyport=<proxyport> & kirc -s 127.0.0.1 -p 6667 alice
Connect to irc.example.org via HTTPS/HTTP proxy server using socat.
.SH DCC FILE TRANSFERS
.B kirc
supports Direct Client-to-Client file transfers, including XDCC file requests
commonly used on IRC file servers.
.PP
When another user sends you a file via DCC SEND, kirc will automatically detect the
incoming file transfer request and begin downloading the file the current working
directory. The file transfer will display:
.PP
.RS
.nf
dcc: receiving <filename> from <sender> (<size> bytes)
.fi
.RE
.PP
Transfer progress and completion messages will appear as the file downloads. To request
a file from an XDCC bot, use the standard XDCC request format:
.PP
.RS
.nf
/ctcp <botname> XDCC SEND #<packet_number>
.fi
.RE
.PP
The bot will initiate a DCC SEND transfer, which kirc will automatically handle. Note
that kirc supports up to 16 simultaneous DCC transfers. Files are saved to the current
working directory with their original filenames.
